# ================================================================
# GymPass Mobile App - Environment Variables (Expo)
# ================================================================
# These are OPTIONAL for simulators/emulators (auto-detected).
# REQUIRED for physical devices or production builds.
#
# Expo reads env vars starting with EXPO_PUBLIC_ prefix.
# These are embedded at build time and visible in client code.
#
# Location: Place this as `.env` in mobile/ root

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# API Configuration
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# API Base URL - where the backend API is hosted
# 
# Auto-detection (if not set):
#   - iOS Simulator: uses http://localhost:4000
#   - Android Emulator: uses http://10.0.2.2:4000
#   - Real device via Expo Go: derives from Expo dev server host
#
# When to set manually:
#   - Running on physical device: set to your computer's LAN IP
#     Example: EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://192.168.1.100:4000
#   - Production builds: set to your production API domain
#     Example: EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://api.gympass.hu
#
# Find your LAN IP:
#   macOS: ipconfig getifaddr en0
#   Windows: ipconfig (look for IPv4 Address)
EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Usage Notes
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Development (Simulators/Emulators):
#   - No env vars needed!
#   - Auto-detection works
#   - Just run: npm start, then press 'i' (iOS) or 'a' (Android)
#
# Development (Physical Device via Expo Go):
#   1. Find your computer's LAN IP (see above)
#   2. Export env before starting:
#      export EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://192.168.1.100:4000
#   3. Run: npx expo start -c
#   4. Scan QR with Expo Go app
#
# Production (EAS Build):
#   1. Set EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL in eas.json or build command
#   2. Example in eas.json:
#      "production": {
#        "env": {
#          "EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL": "https://api.gympass.hu"
#        }
#      }
#   3. Run: eas build --platform ios --profile production
#
# IMPORTANT:
#   - Never put Stripe secrets or backend-only secrets here!
#   - These env vars are embedded in the client app (visible to users)
#   - Only use for non-sensitive configuration (API URLs, feature flags)

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Troubleshooting
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# "Cannot connect to server" error:
#   1. Ensure backend is running (npm run dev in backend/)
#   2. Ensure phone and computer are on same WiFi network
#   3. Check firewall isn't blocking port 4000
#   4. Verify EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL is correct (check console logs)
#   5. Try restarting Expo dev server: npx expo start -c
